posts.name: dino
posts.cooked: As we approach the end of the off-season, we are finalizing our preparations for the upcoming new season. I have a question regarding filament usage. What types of filament do other teams use for 3D printing robot components? We use a Bambu Lab A-1 Mini printer, which has been operational for approximately six to seven months. Currently, we rely on PLA and TPU filaments; while PLA produces high-quality prints, TPU performance has been inconsistent‚Äîwe have yet to master its application effectively. I am keen to learn about filament preferences and practices among other teams in the context of FIRST Robotics Competition, where 3D printing plays a vital role. Thank you in advance for your insights.

posts.name: Jim Sokoloff
posts.cooked:
TPU must remain dry to print effectively. While achieving acceptable prints on TPU was possible, their quality notably enhanced with the use of a filament dryer.  
PLA or PLA-plus are suitable for the majority of our applications such as mounts and shields. At this stage, more advanced materials aren‚Äôt essential due to the current constraints of our program.

posts.name: Brian Bartholmai
posts.cooked: We have had very good luck with PETG. It is very durable, not quite as brittle or stiff as PLA and very easy to print with. Very good bed adhesion, especially on the textured Bamboo bed and MajiGoO or other bed adhesive/release agent. We make some snap-on covers for Swerve modules and clips/spacers for shafts, etc., with PETG where the slight flex is a huge benefit and much easier to print than very flexible TPU on a Bamboo. There is a new formulation on the Bamboo site, PETG-HF, which we don‚Äôt have much experience with but seems very similar to the prior PETG from the few off-season prints we have done. And PETG comes in lime green, which is very important...

posts.name: Nick Aarestad
posts.cooked: 95% of our prints are Bambu PLA Matte. With proper print settings and design, it works fine across various applications, including pulleys, gears, and spacers. We have occasionally used Prusament PCCF and Bambu TPU (we haven't tried TPU HF yet).

We use ABS, TPU, and Carbon fiber nylon for most of our prints. Both cf nylon and tpu need to be dried really good to print well. We do use PLA for prototyping and other small parts but have mostly moved to ABS where we used to use pla all the time.

posts.name: Ian Bae
posts.cooked:
As a team, we primarily use PLA or PLA+ sourced from various vendors, along with occasional TPU prints. We‚Äôve achieved significant success with these materials and don‚Äôt foresee switching away from them since they‚Äôre effective for our requirements.

However, I‚Äôve also conducted prints for my own robotics projects, such as a 3D-printed Swerve Module, where I found PETG and particularly Inland‚Äôs PETG+ filaments to be highly effective. These materials are significantly stronger and less brittle compared to PLA, leading to notable success. Nevertheless, both TPU and PETG have limitations; they must be dried before use, which might necessitate purchasing a filament drying machine by the team.

posts.name: Evan McDonald
posts.cooked: While I haven‚Äôt used any prints on any of my team‚Äôs FRC robots I‚Äôve used a few different filaments on my smaller scale combat robots and I‚Äôve found that 98A TPU has given me the most strength. That being said I‚Äôve never used any CF filaments so they might be stronger for the weight.

posts.name: Sam
posts.cooked: Lately, we've used PLA, PETG, and various Nylon/CF flavors (Onyx, Bambu PAHT-CF, and now Polymaker PA12-CF10). TPU is also a good option. Well-designed and printed PLA/PETG parts are just as competitive as more premium filaments.

In our region, it‚Äôs extremely hot, so everything on the robot must be made from PETG, ABS, or materials with a higher melting point than PLA. We‚Äôve noticed that PLA melts in the trailer when traveling to competitions.

posts.name: Will C
posts.cooked: We use PLA, PETG, TPU, and Nylon-cf, depending on the use case.

posts.name: Aiden B
posts.cooked:
We have 2 Prusas MK3S and 1 Mark One printer. Mentors and students share printers occasionally. We typically use regular PLA for awards or art projects such as team logos and name tags. PETG is used for non-load-bearing spacers, while PC-CF and Onyx are employed for load-bearing components like pivots with Spine XL. We often print gears in PETG, upgrading to PC-CF, and sometimes to metal after encountering issues.  

I‚Äôve heard positive things about PLA+, though we haven‚Äôt tried it yet‚Äîit‚Äôs reportedly excellent for most applications.

posts.name: Tom Line
posts.cooked: Use PLA and polycarbonate because I have the filament. I'm reprinting common thunder hex spacers in sizes 1/16, 1/8, 1/4, and 3/8. A good tip is to use a secondary filament that doesn‚Äôt bond to the main one for support, making removal easier.

posts.name: Kyle Swaidner
posts.cooked: I recently noted a comparison between PETG and PLA materials. While PETG feels sturdy and less brittle than PLA in practical use, it struggles with impact performance and prone to brittle failure under stress, especially at high strain rates. Modern "tough" or "plus" PLA versions often match or exceed PETG's impact toughness depending on the manufacturer. PETG remains a suitable option if higher temperature resistance is needed and alternatives like ABS, ASA, or nylon aren't available.

posts.name: Peyton Yeung
posts.cooked:
Our teams utilize the following materials:

- **eSUN**: PLA+ (a cost-effective option suitable for most non-motion parts)
- **Generic Amazon Special**: PLA Silk (our team color is gold, making it affordable)
- **Bambu Lab**: PLA Basic (bought in bulk for seasonal discounts) and PC (used for tougher components resembling COTS parts), along with Nylon-CF (transitioning more components to nylon-cf as final robot parts).

posts.name: Adam Jenkins
posts.cooked:
Pla is underrated. The problem with heat affecting PLA parts during transportation is significant. We primarily use ABS and ASA, though CF nylon is included, and CF PETG yields excellent results. I'm also experimenting with exotic filaments.

If a material might be exposed to blows, avoid printing it or reinforce it with metal. For materials that are resilient to heat, such as those used in truck loads on hot days, select filaments that can withstand these conditions.

For those who‚Äôve experienced PLA components melting within hot vehicles or trailers, I wonder if anyone has tried PLA+, PLA Pro, or Tough PLA variations.  
In the past, a colleague‚Äôs 3D printerÂèòÂΩ¢when parked in a hot car, which made me aware of the issue. However, switching entirely to PLA+ has prevented similar problems. While I don‚Äôt encounter extreme heat frequently, I often leave robotics outside for long durations. If PLA+ proves insufficient for a task, we opt for TPU or avoid 3DP altogether for that component. The newer PLA+ formulations represent significant advancements and may warrant consideration depending on the application.

posts.name: Rustomac
posts.cooked: I‚Äôve encountered issues with PLA and its tougher versions bending in hot environments. According to Polymaker‚Äôs specifications, their PLA variants have a glass transition temperature of 60¬∞C. Our setup involves a dark trailer in the southern region. We also transport our robot using conventional vehicles to areas like practice fields where intense sunlight is common. On extremely hot days, temperatures can rise to 140¬∞F, prompting us not to use PLA for critical applications. Instead, we opt for PETG and TPU materials.
